# Issue resolver Plugin for SonarQube [![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/willemsrb/sonar-issueresolver-plugin.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/willemsrb/sonar-issueresolver-plugin) [![Quality Gate](https://sonarqube.com/api/badges/gate?key=nl.future-edge.sonarqube.plugins:sonar-issueresolver-plugin)](https://sonarqube.com/dashboard/index?id=nl.future-edge.sonarqube.plugins%3Asonar-issueresolver-plugin)
*Requires SonarQube 6.3+*

This plugin allows you to synchronize and export issue data (status, resolution, assignee, hash, message, creationDate, severity and comments) of issues that have been confirmed, reopened or resolved. After exporting the data you can import it into a project where the issues in that project will be matched with the exported issue data; if matched the issue will be confirmed, reopened or resolved. Optionally the matched issue can be assigned to the same user and missing comments can be added.
When working within one SonarQube installation the issues can be updated between projects directly.

##### Use cases:
- Keeping resolved issues in sync between the master and a release/feature/maintenance branch
- Using the list as a delivery for QA reports

#### Matching issues, assignees and comments
Issues are matched using the component, rule and line-number.
If an issue is  matched it will be reported as 'matched'; if no transition can be determined to reach the exported status and resolution a 'matchFailure' will be reported. If the transition could not be successfully completed a 'transitionFailure' will be reported.

Assignee are matched using the username; the issue will be assigned to the assignee if the username is different and the issue will be reported as 'assigned'. If the assignment could not be succesfully completed an 'assignFailure' will be reported.

Comments are matched by comparing the markdown. If a comment is not present on the issue it will be added and the issue will be reported as 'commented'. If a comment could not be succesfully added a 'commentFailure' will be reported.

#### Resolving issues
When transitioning, assigning issues or adding comments the current logged in account will be used.

## Usage
- Install the plugin via the Update Center in the SonarQube administration pages. Or to install the plugin manually; copy the .jar file from the release to the `extensions/plugins` directory of your SonarQube installation.

- Find the page 'Issue resolver' under the project Administration section.

##### Update
- Select the plugin in the project you want to update issues in. You will need 'Browse' and 'Administer issues' (to resolve issues) permissions for this project.
- Select the 'Update' tab.
- Select the project you want to read issues from. You will need 'Browse' permission for this project.
- Press the 'Update' button to read, match and resolve issues.

##### Export
- Select the plugin in the project you want to export issues for. You will need 'Browse' and 'Administer issues' (to be able to reach the Administration section) permissions for this project.
- Select the 'Export' tab.
- Press the 'Export' button to download a json data file containing the resolved issues from the project.

##### Import
- Select the plugin in the project you want to import issues for. You will need 'Browse' and 'Administer issues' (to resolve issues) permissions for this project.
- Select the 'Import' tab.
- Select the datafile containing the issues to import
- Press the 'Import' button to upload the data file and match and resolve issues.

##### Preview
Use the preview option to preview the matching results. No actual changes will be made to the project.

## Webservices
The main work for the plugin is done via web-services that are available via the SonarQube Web API (see SonarQube -> Helper -> Web API):

- Update issues from another project: http POST to /api/issueresolver/update
- Export issues from a project: http GET to /api/issueresolver/export
- Import issues in a project: http POST to /api/issueresolver/import

These web-services can be used by external tools to trigger the functionality.

1.
  1. 1.3Definitions

| **Definition** | **Explanations** |
| --- | --- |
| Source issue | Any issue from a source project branch that contains the data to be synchronized in a matching target issue. |
| Target issue | Any applicable issue from a target project branch that is a candidate for synchronization. |
| Issue | A violation of a rule at the specific location in a scanned code file. |
| Justification | Justifications are rationales provided by the user to explain why an issue will not be fixed or why an issue is considered as a False-Positive. These justifications are stored in the issue attribute named &quot;comments&quot;. |

1.
  1. 1.4Matching Issues

In order to synchronize issues there is the need to identify those issues from a target branch that are matching reference issues in a source project branch.

As recommended by the sonar support, issues are matching if at least the following conditions are satisfied by both issues:

1. Both issues are raised in the same file (i.e. same file path). This attribute is called a component in the sonar source terminology.
2. Both issues are violating the same rule,
3. Both issues have the same message,

Note: The line (number) where the violation occurs must not be used as it avoids matching similar issues that have only been moved inside their code file.

Note: The message allows differentiating several violations of the same rule (example: use of magic numbers) in the same line of the same file.

1. 2Introduction

The service shall synchronize issue data in a **target** write-enabled project branch from issues in a **source** read-only project branch.

In a source project branch, the issues must be Confirmed, Reopened or Resolved. In the target project branch, all issues are considered. See the status lifecycle in appendix.

The following figure shows the update flow between source and target project branches.

Figure 1: Data Flow between Source and Target Project Branches

1.
  1. 2.1Use Cases

Keep resolved issues in sync between the two project branches.

Note: There shall be no limitations of any kind on the type of branches, whether it is a release/feature/maintenance or master branch, whether it is a short or long lived branch. Synchronisation shall be possible between two distinct projects but also between branches of the same project.

1. 3Sonar References

The following sections are extracted from the SonarQube documentation and reproduced here for information.

1.
  1. 3.1Issue Statuses

After creation, issues flow through a lifecycle, taking on one of five possible statuses:

- **Open**  - set by SonarQube on new issues
- **Confirmed**  - set manually to indicate that the issue is valid
- **Resolved**  - set manually to indicate that the next analysis should _Close_ the issue
- **Reopened**  - set automatically by SonarQube when a _Resolved_ issue hasn&#39;t actually been corrected
- **Closed**  - set automatically by SonarQube for automatically created issues.

1.
  1. 3.2Issue Resolutions

Resolved issues will have one of two resolutions:

- **False Positive**  - set manually
- **Won&#39;t Fix**  - set manually

1. 4Solution Main Services

SONAR-RESOLVER-SERVICES-001

Sonar Resolver Provided Services

The solution shall provide following main services:

1. 1)An export service shall export (in a readable format) issues that are satisfying some &quot;status&quot; conditions.
2. 2)An import service shall import issues data from a file, identify the subset of those that are matching issues in the target project branch in order to synchronise the target issues.
3. 3)An update service shall synchronise issues in a target project branch from matching issues in a source project branch.

1.
  1. 4.1Export Service

This is a read-only feature. The user must have browse permissions on the project branch.

1.
  1.
    1. 4.1.1Export Service Data Flow

The following figure shows the data flow of the export service.

Figure 3: Export Service Data Flow

1.
  1.
    1. 4.1.2Export Service Requirements

SONAR-EXPORT-SERVICE-001

Export Service - Filtering Conditions

The export feature shall export data of issues that have one of the following statuses:

- Confirmed
- Re-Opened
- Resolved

SONAR-EXPORT-SERVICE-002

Export Service - Format of the Generated File

The export feature shall generate a JSON file.

SONAR-EXPORT-SERVICE-003

Export Service - Header of the Generated File

The header of the JSON file shall contain:

- the project key,
- the selected branch
- The export date.

SONAR-EXPORT-SERVICE-004

Export Service – Attributes of an exported Issue

For each issue the following attributes shall be exported:

- The file path – see &quot;long Name&quot; in the example results.
- The rule identifier,
- The line number,
- The hash code,
- The message,
- The status,
- The resolution ,
- The severity,
- The assignee,
- The creation date,
- The comments (as an array of text strings)

Note:  Comments contain the rationales provided by the user to justify that an issue won&#39;t be fixed or that an issue is a False-Positive.

An example of an exported JSON file content is provided in appendix.

  1. 4.2Import Service
    1. 4.2.1Import Service Data Flow

The following figure shows the data flow of the Import Service.

Figure 4: Import Service Data Flow

1.
  1.
    1. 4.2.2Import Service Requirements

SONAR-IMPORT-SERVICE-001

Import Service – Inputs and Outputs

The import service shall:

1. 1)Read reference source issues contained in a JSON input file,
2. 2)Identify the subset of issues found in the target branch that are matching the input issues
3. 3)Update the matching issues in a the target project branch

**Note** : In order to synchronise issues, the user shall have appropriate write permissions on the target project branch.

SONAR-IMPORT-SERVICE-002

Import Service – Transition, Assign and Comment

For each matching issue in the target project branch, the import feature shall:

- transition its status / resolution according to the status / resolution of the issue read in the JSON input file
- assign the issue to the same assignee as found in the source issue ( read in the JSON input file )(only if the target issue has no assignee)
- Add available comments from the matching source issue ( read in the JSON input file ) that are not already in the matching target issue.

**Note** : Transitioning Status/ Resolution, assigning and updating comments are independent. Assigning and commenting is not dependent upon the success of the transitioning.

SONAR-IMPORT-SERVICE-003

Import Service – Preview Mode

The import service shall offer a preview mode. This preview mode shall allow identifying matching issues in the target project branch without proceeding with the changes.

SONAR-IMPORT-SERVICE-004

Import Service – Skip Assignment and Skip Comments

The import service shall offer the option to skip assignments and skip comments.

Skipping assignments means that even if the source issue (read in the JSON file) is assigned and the current target issue is not, the assignee of the source issue (read in the JSON file) won&#39;t be assigned to the current target issue.

Skipping comments means that even if the source issue (read in the JSON file) has comments (that are not yet in the current target issue), these source comments won&#39;t be reported in the current target issue.

SONAR-IMPORT-SERVICE-005

Import Service – Results Format

The results of the import shall be presented in a table that can be easily copied for instance in an EXCEL file.

An example of a results table is provided in the appendix.

SONAR-UPDATE-SERVICE-001

Update Service – Source and Target Project Branch Issues

The update service shall synchronise issues in a target project branch from matching issues read in a source (read-only) project branch.

In the source project branch, only Confirmed, Resolved or ReOpened issues are considered. In the target project branch, all issues are considered.

SONAR-UPDATE-SERVICE-002

Update Service – Preview Mode

The update service shall have a preview mode allowing identifying the &quot;to be modified&quot; target issues without proceeding with the changes.

SONAR-UPDATE-SERVICE-003

Update Service – Skip Assignment and Skip Comments

The update service shall offer the option to skip assignments and skip comments.

SONAR-UPDATE-SERVICE-004

Update Service – Results Format

The update results shall be presented in a table that can be easily exported in an EXCEL file.

1.
  1. 4.4Results

This section defines the results that shall be presented to the user.

SONAR-UPDATE-RESULTS-001

Update Service – Results Content

Results shall detail:

1. 1)The issues that have been matched
2. 2)The subset of the target issues that have been transitioned.
3. 3)The subset of the target issues that have been assigned.
4. 4)The subset of target issues whose comments were updated from the source issue comments.

An example of results is provided in the Appendix.

1.
  1. 4.5Issues filtering conditions

SONAR-UPDATE-FILTERING-001

Update Service – Filtering Conditions

Filtering criteria are a set of conditions to consider issues from a **source** project branch. Only issues with the following statuses shall be considered:

- CONFIRMED,
- REOPENED,
- RESOLVED

Note: When analysing a target project branch, all issues are considered without any status condition.

1.
  1. 4.6Issues Matching Criteria

Matching criteria are a set of conditions to consider a source reference issue matching a &quot;to be synchronised&quot; issue of a target project branch.

Matching criteria defines the criteria that need to be satisfied to modify the target issue.

SONAR-UPDATE-MATCHING-001

Update Service – Matching Conditions

Any source issue shall be matching a target issue when the following conditions are satisfied:

1. 1)Same Component i.e. same file path,
2. 2)same rule id,
3. 3)same line
4. 4)same message

SONAR-UPDATE-SYNC-001

Update Service – Synchronisation

The following modifications shall be applied to the target issue:

- status is transitioned to the status of the source issue
- resolution is modified to the resolution of the source issue
- Source assignee is assigned only if the target issue is not yet assigned
- Any comment from the source issue that is not already in the target issue is added to the target issue.

1.
  1. 4.7Issues Status Transitioning Automate

SONAR-UPDATE-SYNC-002

Update Service – Transitioning Automate

The following sections show the conditions that shall be satisfied to perform a transition.

Current = concerns the target issue (the issue to be synchronised)

Wanted = concerns the source read-only issue.

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.1Case where no transition

Current status = Reopened **AND**  Wanted status = Reopened AND Current resolution = Wanted resolution

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.2Confirm Transition

Wanted status = confirmed **AND**  ( current status = Open **OR** current status = Reopened )

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.3Un-confirm transition

Wanted status = Reopened **AND**  current status = Confirmed

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.4Re open transition

Wanted status = Reopened **AND**  current status = Resolved

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.5Resolve transition

Wanted status = Resolved **AND**  ( Current Status = OPEN   **OR** Current status = reopened   **OR** current status = Confirmed)

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.6Resolve False positive transition

All conditions of the resolve transition **AND**   Wanted Resolution = False positive

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.7Resolve Won&#39;t fix transition

All conditions of resolve transition AND   Wanted Resolution = WONT\_FIX

1.
  1.
    1. 4.7.8All other cases

An error message is returned. No transition is performed.

1. 5Test cases

This section describes specific test cases defined following the discussion held with the sonar source support. These discussions were around the criteria to match a source and a target issue.

1.
  1. 5.1Case where there are several issues on the same line

This test case is recalled here as it is one specific condition to be tested in order to report issues attributes between multiple identical issues raised on the same line.

Case where there are several issues on the same line: example is when several magic numbers are used in one line: circle = 2 \* 3.14 \* radius).

1.
  1. 5.2Case where the issue has no line information or the line information equals zero

This case is specific to issues that are applicable for a whole file.

1.
  1. 5.3Case where the code containing a violation has only been moved inside a file

As explained by the sonar source support, a violation hash-code is not modified if a piece of code is only moved inside a file. The sonar support also explained that the text of the code raising the violation might have more or less spaces; the hash-code of both violations would be identical.

1.
  1. 6.2Matching Strategies

Suggestion formulée par le support sonar :

Pour plusieurs raisons, l&#39;identification de 2 issues identiques sur 2 branches ne peut être certaine que dans un certain nombre de cas, les plus fréquents. Il faut toutefois s&#39;attendre à ce que dans une fraction des cas, il y ait &quot;une bonne probabilité&quot; que les issues soient les mêmes sans que cela soit « certain » à 100%. Dans ce cas, je recommande fortement de loguer les 2 issues à comparer et de faire une comparaison manuelle (ça devrait correspondre à un petit nombre d&#39;issues). Essayer de corréler automatiquement 2 issues pas strictement identiques est trop risqué, il y a trop de cas difficiles à anticiper.

 Les champs à considérer en premier sont: Component (File), Rule et Hash.

- La ligne n&#39;est pas fiable (beaucoup moins que le hash). Si du code est ajouté ou supprimé avant la ligne de l&#39;issue, la ligne est décalée.
- Note que le hash n&#39;est pas non plus fiable à 100%. Si la ligne est modifiée (autre chose que des espaces) le hash le sera aussi, mais c&#39;est moins fréquent que des décalages de ligne.
- Le champ message peut aussi aider à discriminer 2 violations identiques sur la même ligne. Souvent les messages &quot;nomment&quot; l&#39;objet de la violation (une variable ou autre) et donc on peut faire le distinguo.

Donc:

- Si le Component, Rule et Hash sont identiques le match est bon à 99% - Seul le cas de 2 issues identiques sur la même ligne n&#39;est pas couvert.
- Tous les autres champs (Line, Message, Type, Severity, CreationDate...) ne peuvent que renforcer la probabilité de match lorsque, par exemple le hash ne correspond pas.

Ma recommandation est d&#39;implémenter une logique simple qui couvrira 95% des cas, 100% déterministes (match de File, Rule et Hash, plus une seule issue sur la ligne), et le loguer en manuel tous les corners cases, très difficiles à gérer de manière fiable en automatique.
